Composer [Tyler](Brian)(Brian Tyler (composer)) announced on his official website that he had been hired to write original music for the film. Tyler previously worked with Stallone on *[Rambo](Rambo (2008 film))* in 2008.

[Godsmack](Godsmack) vocalist [Erna](Sully)(Sully Erna) was approached by Stallone himself to write a song for the film. Erna showed him a potential unfinished piece of "[Prayer](Sinners)(Sinner's Prayer (song))"; Stallone liked it and wanted to use it in the film. However, during the film's post-production, the scene that "Sinner's Prayer" was originally meant to be used in was reworked and the song was taken off the film and its soundtrack. The American hard rock band [Shinedown](Shinedown) contributed a brand new track, "[Eyes (Boom-Lay Boom-Lay Boom)](Diamond)(Diamond Eyes (Boom-Lay Boom-Lay Boom))", recorded specifically for the film, but the song does not appear in the film nor its official soundtrack. The song was used in the theatrical trailer and the finished piece was released on June 15, 2010. Both songs were finally used for the Extended Director's Cut. One of the alternate trailers uses the song "[City](Paradise)(Paradise City)" by [N' Roses](Guns)(Guns N' Roses). [Google](Google)  The song "[Boys Are Back in Town](The)(The Boys Are Back in Town)" by [Lizzy](Thin)(Thin Lizzy) (live version featured on *[Dangerous](Still)(Still Dangerous)*) played in TV spots and is played over the credits. [Google](Google)

The score for the film was released on August 10. The track lists have been revealed.

## In service

, there are 64 passenger ships over 135,000GT in service. The first ships over that size were the  ships from [Caribbean Group](Royal)(Royal Caribbean Group)'s [Caribbean International](Royal)(Royal Caribbean International) (RCI). These ships, which debuted in 1998 at over 137,000GT, were almost 30,000GT larger than the next-largest cruise ships, and were some of the first ships designed to appeal to "non-cruisers", with features like a four-deck-high,  atrium down the center of the ship, an [rink](ice)(ice rink), and a [wall](climbing)(climbing wall). In 2005, the five *Voyager*-class ships were overtaken by the 149,215GT  (*QM2*), the first non-RCI passenger ship over 135,000GT and the only passenger ship currently in service that classifies itself as an [liner](ocean)(ocean liner). The *QM2* was surpassed by RCI's 155,889 GT -class vessels in 2006, which were in turn overtaken by RCI's first of six planned  vessels in 2009. The *Oasis*-class ships, at over 225,000GT, are at least  wide,  high, and accommodate over 5,400 passengers.

Since 2008, other cruise lines have been ordering 135,000+GT ships. [Cruises](MSC)(MSC Cruises) introduced the first of four 137,936–139,072 GT s in 2008, followed in 2017 by both the 153,516 GT  and the 171,598–181,541 GT . [Cruise Line](Norwegian)(Norwegian Cruise Line) debuted the 155,873 GT *Norwegian Epic* in 2010, the first ship outside of the *Oasis* class with a double-occupancy capacity of over 4,000, and introduced the 145,655 GT  in 2013 and the 165,157–169,116-GT *Breakaway*-plus class in 2015. Cruise lines belonging to [Corporation & plc](Carnival)(Carnival Corporation & plc), [Cruises](Princess)(Princess Cruises) and [Cruises](P&O)(P&O Cruises), debuted the first of seven 142,714 GT+  ships in 2013, and the corporation's [Cruise Line](Carnival)(Carnival Cruise Line), [Cruises](Costa)(Costa Cruises), and [Cruises](AIDA)(AIDA Cruises) debuted the first of seven planned 133,596–135,225 GT  ships in 2016. , the first of Carnival Corporation's nine planned  ships, debuted in 2018 at 183,858GT, with future ships in the class planned for Costa, P&O, Carnival, and AIDA. In 2016 and 2017, [Hong Kong](Genting)(Genting Hong Kong)'s [Cruises](Dream)(Dream Cruises) introduced the 150,695 GT  and , the first large ships from an Asian-owned cruise line.

